{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Paritosh K. Pandya |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = <!-- {{birth-date|df=yes|...}} --> |birth_place = [[India]] |residence = [[Mumbai]], India |citizenship = |nationality = Indian |fields = |workplaces = [[Oxford University Computing Laboratory]], [[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]] |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = [[Mathai Joseph]] |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = [[Duration Calculus|DCVALID]]<ref name="dcvalid">{{cite web| url=http://www.tcs.tifr.res.in/~pandya/dcvalid.html | title=DCVALID: A tool for modelchecking Duration Calculus Formulae | first=Paritosh | last=Pandya | publisher=[[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]] | location=India | date=1997–2001 | accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = [[Tony Hoare]] |influenced = |awards = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }}
'''Paritosh K. Pandya''' is an Indian [[computer scientist]] based at the [[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]] (TIFR) in [[Mumbai]], [[India]].
Paritosh Pandya studied for a BE degree in [[Electronics]] at the [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]] (1980), MTech degree in [[Computer Science]] at [[IIT Kanpur]] (1982), and a [[PhD]] in Computer Science at [[Bombay University]]/TIFR (1988).<ref name="bio">{{cite web| url=http://www.tcs.tifr.res.in/~pandya/bio.ps | title=Curriculum Vitae: Paritosh K. Pandya | publisher=[[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]] | location=India | accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref>
From 1988, Paritosh Pandya has held academic posts at TIFR.<ref name="bio" /> He was a researcher at the [[Oxford University Computing Laboratory]] in [[England]] during 1989–91, on leave from TIFR, undertaking research with [[Jonathan Bowen]], [[Jifeng He]], and [[Tony Hoare]], amongst others, as part of the [[European Strategic Program on Research in Information Technology|ESPRIT]] ProCoS project on "Provably Correct Systems". He then returned to TIFR, where he has spent most of his career. Pandya leads the [[Theoretical computer science|Theoretical Computer Science]] Group there.
Pandya's main research interest is in the area of [[formal methods]], including [[real-time system]]s. He has been especially involved with research concerning [[Duration Calculus]], including the DCVALID [[model-checking]] tool.<ref name="dcvalid" /> His most cited paper, "''Finding Response Times in a Real-Time System''", with over 900 citations on [[Google Scholar]],<ref>{{cite web| url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?view_op=view_citation&hl=en&user=M_FgkWsAAAAJ&citation_for_view=M_FgkWsAAAAJ:u5HHmVD_uO8C| title=Finding response times in a real-time system | publisher=[[Google Scholar]] | accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref> was joint work with [[Mathai Joseph]], published in ''[[The Computer Journal]]'' in 1986.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://comjnl.oxfordjournals.org/content/29/5/390.short | first1=Mathai | last1=Joseph | first2=Paritosh | last2=Pandya | authorlink1=Mathai Joseph | title=Finding Response Times in a Real-Time System | journal=[[The Computer Journal]] | publisher=[[British Computer Society|BCS]] |year=1986 | volume=29 | number=5 | pages=390–395 |doi=10.1093/comjnl/29.5.390 | accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref>
Paritosh Pandya has been a member of the [[Editorial Board]] for the ''[[Formal Aspects of Computing]]'' journal published by [[Springer-Verlag|Springer]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://link.springer.com/journal/165/edboard | title=Editorial Board | work=[[Formal Aspects of Computing]] | publisher=[[Springer-Verlag|Springer]] | accessdate=29 January 2014 }}</ref>
