'''Robert Brown (Robby) Gardner''' (February 27, 1939 – May 5, 1998) was an [[United States|American]] [[mathematician]] who worked on [[differential geometry]], a field in which he obtained several novel results.<ref name=remembering>{{citation | last = Wilkens | first = George R. | contribution = Remembering the mathematics of Robert Brown Gardner | contribution-url = http://www.math.hawaii.edu/~grw/Gardner/gardner.pdf | doi = 10.1090/pspum/064/1654541 | location = Providence, RI | mr = 1654541 | pages = 1–10 | publisher = American Mathematical Society | series = Proceedings of Symposia in Pure Mathematics | title = Differential geometry and control (Boulder, CO, 1997) | volume = 64 | year = 1999}}</ref> He was the author and co-author of three influential books, produced more than fifty papers,<ref>[http://www.unc.edu/math/Faculty/pbe/robbypapers.html Publications of Robert Gardner]</ref> eighteen masters students and thirteen Ph.D students.<ref name="cv">[http://www.unc.edu/math/Faculty/pbe/robbyvita.html Curriculum vitae of Robert Gardner]</ref><ref name="unc">[http://www.unc.edu/math/Faculty/pbe/memoriam.html Robert Gardner, in memoriam]</ref> His 1991 book, ''Exterior Differential Systems'', coauthored with R. Bryant [[Robert Bryant (mathematician)|Robert Bryant]], S. S. Chern [[Shiing-Shen Chern]], H. Goldschmidt and P. Griffiths [[Phillips Griffiths]], is the standard reference for the subject.<ref name="remembering"/> [[Robert Bryant (mathematician)|Robert Bryant]], [[Duke University]]'s Professor of Mathematics and the president of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (2015-2017) was a student of his.<ref name=gene>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.ams.org/id.php?id=22424 |title=Mathematics Genealogy Project|publisher=genealogy.ams.org|accessdate=2015-06-29}}</ref>
He is better known in the United States for his improvements and popularization of the methods of [[Élie Cartan]] (most notably, [[Cartan's equivalence method]], an [[algorithm]]ic procedure for determining if two geometric shapes are different). The works of Cartan were hard to grasp for most students, and Gardner worked to explain them in more accessible ways.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kristine K. Fowler|title=Using the Mathematics Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i2mu7jg6OHEC&pg=PA184|date=25 May 2004|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8247-5035-0|page=184}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Jerrold E. Marsden|author2=Tudor Ratiu|title=The Breadth of Symplectic and Poisson Geometry: Festschrift in Honor of Alan Weinstein|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lG4Gt_fyx4UC&pg=PA84|date=3 July 2007|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-0-8176-4419-2|page=84}}</ref>
==Biography== He was born on February 27, 1939. Gardner graduated from [[Princeton University]] in 1959,<ref name="unc"/> earned a master's degree from [[Columbia University]] in 1960,<ref name="cv"/> and completed his [[doctorate of philosophy|PhD]] in 1965 from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], under the orientation of [[Shiing-Shen Chern]].<ref name="gene"/> After this, he worked at many places, including becoming a member of the [[Institute for Advanced Study]], and some years as assistant professor at [[Columbia University]]. He joined the faculty of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] in 1971 and became a full professor there in 1977.<ref name="unc"/> He died on May 5, 1998.
==Legacy== In his memory, the UNC Mathematics Department created the Robert Brown Gardner Memorial Fund, devoted to supporting graduate student activities.<ref name="unc"/>
==Selected publications== *''The Method of Equivalence and Its Applications'' {{ISBN|978-0-89871-240-7}} *R. Bryant, S.-S. Chern, R. B. Gardner, H. Goldschmidt, P. Griffiths, ''Exterior Differential Systems'', [[Mathematical Sciences Research Institute|MSRI Publications]], Springer, 1990 *''Lectures on Exterior Algebras Over Commutative Rings'' *''Differential Geometric Methods in Partial Differential Equations''
